    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Thanks for the solution.\n\nI work on Linux also, so the aliases under Linux shells, do allow\narguments.\nSo when you want to design something, e.g. alias under powershell,\nyou would do some research to see in other platforms, how they have\nimplemented,\nand take the best or if possible improve upon it. That is why it is\nbaffling.\nOf course you can say that the Linux implementation is wrong, as far as the\ndefinition of alias goes.\nI am sure some body in the microsoft design team had a good reason not to\nsupport the alias arguments.\nJust thinking out loud.\n\nThanks\nsguha\n\nOn Mon, Mar 11, 2019 at 10:44 AM vexx32 <notifications@github.com> wrote:\n\n> Aliases are designed to essentially just register a new name for the same\n> command, and don't really provide for supplying arguments as well. For\n> example, cd is an alias to Set-Location. You can provide it all the same\n> arguments, but it supplies no arguments of its own.\n>\n> For what you want, you'd simply define a new function:\n>\n> function toRootDir { Set-Location 'C:\\' }\n>\n> â€”\n> You are receiving this because you authored the thread.\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\n> <https://github.com/PowerShell/PowerShell/issues/9105#issuecomment-471646727>,\n> or mute the thread\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/ASd7E_6nVyloEqWqWLtdGNctooENuBNaks5vVpYagaJpZM4bnh4y>\n> .\n>\n",
